Bio334 Exercise 5 (Robinson): Single-cell RNA-seq session

Almut LÃ¼tge, Helena L Crowell, Anthony Sonrel, Mark Robinson

Compiled: June 02, 2022

Background

During the last years, single cell RNAseq became a popular method in the field of genomics. Different technologies and protocols were developed and optimized in parallel. Some of them were generated to perform a specific subtask (e.g.Â single nucleus sequencing), while most of them differ in the number of cells that could be processed and sequencing depth (the amount of the cellâs total RNA that is sequenced) that can be achieved. Well known technologies are:

  • 10X Chromium, which enables sequencing of tens of thousands of cells at relatively low cost, but to a comparably shallow depth.
  • Dropseq, a non-commercial protocol with lower throughput than 10X chromium.
  • CELseq, which also has a lower throughput, but highest sequencing depth.

Dataset

For this exercise, we will use data from the CellBench package. These data contain gene counts of cells from 3 different lung cancer cell lines that were sequenced using 10X chromium, Drop-seq and Smart-seq. We will use them to compare the effects of these technologies. This is a benchmark dataset and cell lines were used to represent variability comparable to that observed when multiple cell types are observed in a sample (e.g., consider sampling the cells in blood; various immune cell types, such as T cells, B cells and monocytes, would be present and they should exhibit distinguishable gene expression programs). Here the data have already been preprocessed, so we donât need to worry about filtering low quality cells. The package already contains raw and normalized counts and provides the user with the cell line label (i.e., we know in advance which cell originates from which cell line).

Merge datasets

Once you are familiar with the different objects, you can start to investigate the effect of the different sequencing technologies. To do so, it is easier to merge them into one SingleCellexperiment object. This is basically like adding new cells to an existing SingleCellexperiment object. Unfortunately, this can only be done for the same genes and metadata columns, so we first need to find the overlapping genes and colData.

Question: What are potential drawbacks of this method?

Hint: Check your results from above.

Solution: before merging SingleCellExperiment objects we have to reduce them to a common list of genes. As shown in the first figure of the demo, an assay can be extended with more cells but they all need to have information about the same set of genes (rows of the matrix).

As you can see above, all 3 matrices have different dimensions. By merging them, we will loose the information of all the genes that were not shared among the 3 experiments. As the gene detection rate (probability to sequence a transcript that is expressed) depends on the library size and expression of other genes this can influence downstream results (e.g., there is an interdependence between the counts of different genes). Thus discarding genes that are not shared between experiments should always be done carefully.

# create list of `SingleCellExperiment` objects
sce_list <- list(tenx, drop_seq, cel_seq) %>% 
  set_names(c("tenx", "drop_seq", "celseq"))

# find intersection of genes
intersect_genes <- Reduce(intersect, lapply(sce_list, rownames))

# find common columns
overlap_cols <- Reduce(intersect, 
                       lapply(sce_list, function(u) names(colData(u))))

# subset each object to according to common genes/columns
sce_list <- lapply(sce_list, function(sce){
    sce_sub <- sce[intersect_genes,]
    colData(sce_sub) <- colData(sce)[, overlap_cols]
    sce_sub
})

# `cbind` the objects together
sce_com <- do.call(SingleCellExperiment::cbind, sce_list)

# assign vector w/ technology
sce_com$technology <- rep(names(sce_list), 
                          sapply(sce_list, ncol))

# assign unique cellnames
colnames(sce_com) <- rownames(colData(sce_com)) <- paste0(sce_com$technology, 
                                                          "_", colnames(sce_com))

# if you need to free some memory
rm(sce_list, tenx, drop_seq, cel_seq)

# Principal component analysis (PCA)
# Find highly variable genes
dec <- modelGeneVar(sce_com)
top.hvgs <- getTopHVGs(dec, n = 2000)
sce_com <- runPCA(sce_com, subset_row = top.hvgs)

#Tsne
sce_com <- runTSNE(sce_com)
# plot PCA and Tsne
multiplot(cols = 2,
  plotPCA(sce_com, colour_by = "technology") + 
    ggtitle("PCA - Different technologies"),

# Find markers
markers <- findMarkers(sce_com,
  groups = sce_com$cluster,
  pval.type = "all",
  lfc = 1, 
  block = sce_com$technology,
  direction = "up")

  • (optional) Try to find a suitable reference database in the celldex package and use it to annotate the cells. Do you see a problem with the annotation ? If yes, why ?

Solution:

# Let's try to use an immune reference dataset as we are working with cancer cell lines
# Warning: we ask here ENSEMBL gene IDs as our dataset is also using these gene names
ref <- MonacoImmuneData(ensembl = TRUE)
# Predict cell types
pred <- SingleR(test=sce_com, ref=ref, labels=ref$label.main)
table(pred$labels)
## 
##         B cells    CD4+ T cells Dendritic cells       Monocytes     Progenitors 
##             116               4             929              16             336
# Plot the scores for each cell-type
plotScoreHeatmap(pred)

# Plot cell-types in dimension reduction
sce_com$singler.label <- pred$labels
plotTSNE(sce_com, colour_by = "singler.label") + 
    ggtitle("SingleR reference-based annotation")

# The cell-types don't regroup per cluster and there is a strong overlap of high scores on the heatmap. This is an indication that the predictions can be biased. 
# One reason could be the absence of lung reference dataset in celldex. This is a common problem with reference-based annotation: the quality of the predictions highly depends on the availability of the references.
